<h1>Two sample inference</h1>




<h3>Mann Whitney U-test</h3>

We have same set up as before. We want to test

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

or

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/sgt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

or

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/slt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>


Define 

<blockquote>
D<sub>ij</sub> = I{X<sub>i</sub>  &lt;  Y<sub>j</sub>}, for all
i,j.
</blockquote>

Then Mann Whitney U-test uses the test statistic

<blockquote>
U = 
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
    align=middle>
    
    <sub>i</sub>
                <img src=
                "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
                align=middle>
                
                <sub>j</sub> D<sub>ij</sub>
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.1:</font></b> 
   
   Consider the three alternative hypothesies listed
   above. When should we reject H<sub>0</sub> in favour of each of them, for
   large or small U?
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
Let 

<blockquote>
&theta; = E(D<sub>ij</sub>)<br>
&theta;<sub>1</sub> = E(D<sub>ij</sub>D<sub>ik</sub>)<br>
&theta;<sub>2</sub> = E(D<sub>ij</sub>D<sub>kj</sub>)
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.2:</font></b> 
   
   Compute &theta; under H<sub>0</sub>.
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show that if H<sub>0</sub> is true then 
   
   <blockquote>
   &theta;<sub>1</sub> = &theta;<sub>2</sub> = 1/3.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.4:</font></b> 
   
   Compute E(U) in general, as well as under H<sub>0</sub>.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.5:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   cov(D<sub>ij</sub>D<sub>kl</sub>) = 
   </td>
   <td>
    0 
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   
   if i 
        <img src=
        "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
        align=top>
        
         k and j 
                 <img src=
                 "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
                 align=top>
                 
                  l
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
    &theta;-&theta;<sup2</sup>
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   
   if i=k and j=l
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
    &theta;<sub>1</sub>-&theta;<sup2</sup>
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   
   if i=k and j 
                <img src=
                "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
                align=top>
                
                 l
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   &theta;<sub>2</sub>-&theta;<sup2</sup>
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   
   if i 
        <img src=
        "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
        align=top>
        
         k and j=l
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   



<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.6:</font></b> 
   
   Use the last exercise to show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Var(U) = 
   mn(&theta;-&theta;<sup2</sup>)
   +mn(m-1)(&theta;<sub>2</sub>-&theta;<sup2</sup>)
   +mn(n-1)(&theta;<sub>1</sub>-&theta;<sup2</sup>),
   </blockquote>
   
   in general. Check that this reduces to
   
   <blockquote>
   mn(m+n+1)/12
   </blockquote>
   
   under H<sub>0</sub>.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.7:</font></b> 
   
   Argue that U is distribution-free under H<sub>0</sub> by showing that
   
   <blockquote>
   P(U = u) = r<sub>mn</sub>(u)/
                                <sup>m+n</sup>C<sub>m</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   under H<sub>0</sub>, where
   
   <blockquote>
   r<sub>mn</sub>(u) = number of arrangements of m X's and n Y's
   such that the number of times an X precedes an Y is u.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.8:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   r<sub>mn</sub>(u) = r<sub>mn</sub>(mn-u)
   </blockquote>
   
   Hnece conclude that undr H<sub>0</sub>, U is distributed symmetrically
   around mn/2. 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Theorem:</b>
   
   For large m,n,
   
   <blockquote>
   (U-E(U))/sqrt(Var(U)) ~ AN(0,1).
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   
<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
Shall do later using a theorem for U-statistics.
<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>



<h3>An estimation problem</h3>

We can use the above idea to get a confidence interval for a two sample
location problem. We have the same set up as above. But now we also assume
that G is a location shift of F, i.e.,

<blockquote>
G(x) = F(x- &theta;) for all x,
</blockquote>

where &theta; is  unknown. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.9:</font></b> 
   
   Which of the following two statements is true under this model?
   
   <blockquote>
   Y<sub>1</sub>-&theta;, ..., Y<sub>n</sub>-&theta; are iid
   F
   </blockquote>
   
   or 
   
   <blockquote>
   Y<sub>1</sub>+&theta;, ..., Y<sub>n</sub>+&theta; are iid
   F ?
   </blockquote>
   
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Define 

<blockquote>
U(&theta;) = 
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
             align=middle>
             
             <sub>i</sub>
                         <img src=
                         "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
                         align=middle>
                         
                         <sub>j</sub> I{Zij
  &gt;  0)
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.10:</font></b> 
   
   Show that U(&theta;) has distribution free of &theta;. In particular,
   show that its distribution is same as the null distribution of the
   Mann-Whitney U statistic under H<sub>0</sub>.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
Suppose that we are given &alpha;, and we want to get a
(1-&alpha;)-level CI for &theta;. Since U(&theta;) has a completely
known distribution, hence we can find integer c such that

<blockquote>
P(c 
    <img src=
    "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
    align=top>
    
     U(&theta;) 
                <img src=
                "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                align=top>
                
                 mn-c) = 1-&alpha;.
</blockquote>

Due to the discrete nature of U(&theta;), the equality may not
hold exactly. Next, order the mn differences, Z<sub>ij</sub>'s, as

<blockquote>
W<sub>1</sub> &lt; ... &lt; W<sub>mn</sub>
</blockquote>

The inequalities are strict with probability 1, because of the
continuity assumption on F. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.11:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   {c 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
      align=top>
      
       U(&theta;) 
                  <img src=
                  "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                  align=top>
                  
                   mn-c}  iff  {W<sub>c</sub> &lt;
   &theta;  &lt;  W<sub>mn-c+1</sub>}
   </blockquote>
   
   Hnece argue that (W<sub>c</sub>, W<sub>mn-c+1</sub>) is a
   (1-&alpha;)-level CI for &theta;. 
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       See the hint for ONE.7.
       ]
       </i>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<h4>Hodges-Lehmann approach</h4>

Recall that we had described the HL approach for one sample problem as a
method to obtain point estimates from a test. We can apply this aproach to
Mann-Whitney U-test to get a two sample HL estimate for &theta; as
follows.
<p>
Notice that U(&theta;) is distributed symmetrically around mn/2. The HL
approach suggests choosing 
                           <img src=
                           "resources/statinf2/thetahat.png"
                           align=top>
                           
                            in a way so that U(
                                               <img src=
                                               "resources/statinf2/thetahat.png"
                                               align=top>
                                               
                                               )
is as close 
to mn/2 as possible. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise MANN.12:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/thetahat.png"
   align=top>
   
    = median of the Z<sub>ij</sub>'s.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


